question content: Which subject area do you/ do you expect to work with Teaching Lab on this year?
What does “rigor” mean in math instruction, as defined by the instructional shifts?
choice: Giving students opportunities to develop deep commands of the how, why, and when of mathematical concepts.

question content: Please complete this statement: Eliciting and using student thinking is an equitable teaching practice because this practice...
choice: Give students a chance to share and develop their thinking.

question content: Which of the following actions BEST describes equitable instructional strategies for supporting students with unfinished learning in math?
choice: Identifying unfinished learning leading up to the current topic and teach 1-2 lessons targeting those prerequisites at the beginning of the topic.

question content: Teachers should be color blind when it comes to their teaching - They shouldn’t think of their students in terms of their race or ethnicity.
Which of the following best describes your role?
The gap in the achievement among students of different races is about poverty, not race.
Teachers should keep in mind the limits of their students’ ability and give them assignments that they can do so that they do not become discouraged.
Before students are asked to engage in complex learning tasks, they need to have a solid grasp of basic skills.
It is not fair to ask students who are struggling with English to take on challenging academic assignments.
Teachers should provide all students the opportunity to work with grade-level texts and tasks.
To be honest, students have a certain amount of intelligence, and they really can’t do much to change it.
Your intelligence is something about you that you can’t change very much.
If a child doesn’t learn something the first time, the teacher should try another way.
If the teacher provides the proper scaffolds, all students in the class will be able to succeed with grade-level texts and tasks.
Equitable instruction in math includes which of the following?
choice: Creating opportunities for students to practice saying out loud how they solved for a problem.

question content: Which of the following questions will give you the LEAST amount of insight into what the student is thinking?
Which of the following is the LEAST effective method of helping students understand and make connections between representations?
choice: Explicitly teaching students how to use certain representations.

Note - The curriculum refers to what Teaching Lab is supporting you on this year.
Which subject area do you/ do you expect to work with Teaching Lab on this year?
What does “rigor” mean in math instruction, as defined by the instructional shifts?
choice: Giving students opportunities to develop deep commands of the how, why, and when of mathematical concepts.

question content: Please complete this statement: Eliciting and using student thinking is an equitable teaching practice because this practice...
choice: Give students a chance to share and develop their thinking.

question content: Which of the following actions BEST describes equitable instructional strategies for supporting students with unfinished learning in math?
choice: Ensuring that students have all the prerequisite skills from prior content before beginning new grade-level work.

question content: Teachers should be color blind when it comes to their teaching - They shouldn’t think of their students in terms of their race or ethnicity.
Which of the following best describes your role?
I am color blind when it comes to my teaching - I don’t think of my students in terms of their race or ethnicity.
I try to keep in mind the limits of my students’ ability and give them assignments that I know they can do so that they do not become discouraged.
The gap in the achievement among students of different races is about poverty, not race.
Before students are asked to engage in complex learning tasks, they need to have a solid grasp of basic skills.
It is not fair to ask students who are struggling with English to take on challenging academic assignments.
Teachers should provide all students the opportunity to work with grade-level texts and tasks.
To be honest, students have a certain amount of intelligence, and they really can’t do much to change it.
Your intelligence is something about you that you can’t change very much.
If a child doesn’t learn something the first time, I will try another way.
If I provide the proper scaffolds, all students in my class will be able to succeed with grade-level texts and tasks.
Equitable instruction in math includes which of the following?
choice: Creating opportunities for students to practice saying out loud how they solved for a problem.

question content: Which of the following questions will give you the LEAST amount of insight into what the student is thinking?
Which of the following is the LEAST effective method of helping students understand and make connections between representations?
choice: Explicitly teaching students how to use certain representations.

question content: Teachers should be color blind when it comes to their teaching - They shouldn’t think of their students in terms of their race or ethnicity.
Which of the following best describes your role?
I am color blind when it comes to my teaching - I don’t think of my students in terms of their race or ethnicity.
I try to keep in mind the limits of my students’ ability and give them assignments that I know they can do so that they do not become discouraged.
The gap in the achievement among students of different races is about poverty, not race.
Before students are asked to engage in complex learning tasks, they need to have a solid grasp of basic skills.
It is not fair to ask students who are struggling with English to take on challenging academic assignments.
Teachers should provide all students the opportunity to work with grade-level texts and tasks.
To be honest, students have a certain amount of intelligence, and they really can’t do much to change it.
Your intelligence is something about you that you can’t change very much.
If a child doesn’t learn something the first time, I will try another way.
If I provide the proper scaffolds, all students in my class will be able to succeed with grade-level texts and tasks.
Do you work with grades K-2 in ELA/Literacy?

I am confident that I am implementing the curriculum in a way that maximizes positive impact for student learning.

question content: Mrs. Richards’ students have a range of reading proficiency and knowledge about the food chain. When reading a grade-level complex text about this topic, which group of students is most likely to perform better on comprehension questions?
choice: Cannot say. The research is inconclusive about the relationship between content knowledge and comprehension.

question content: How could Mrs. Richards best prepare students to build knowledge about the topic of the food chain?
choice: Have students answer a series of text-dependent questions after reading the main text.

question content: The main text that the students in Ms. Blackwell’s class is about to read is likely to be very difficult for the majority of the class. Which of the following is a strategy that Ms. Blackwell could use with her students with lower reading abilities?
choice: Provide students with lower reading abilities an audio version of the main text to listen to before reading the main text in class.

question content: Teachers should be color blind when it comes to their teaching - They shouldn’t think of their students in terms of their race or ethnicity.
Which of the following best describes your role?
The gap in the achievement among students of different races is about poverty, not race.
Teachers should keep in mind the limits of their students’ ability and give them assignments that they can do so that they do not become discouraged.
Before students are asked to engage in complex learning tasks, they need to have a solid grasp of basic skills.
It is not fair to ask students who are struggling with English to take on challenging academic assignments.
Teachers should provide all students the opportunity to work with grade-level texts and tasks.
To be honest, students have a certain amount of intelligence, and they really can’t do much to change it.
Your intelligence is something about you that you can’t change very much.
If a child doesn’t learn something the first time, the teacher should try another way.
If the teacher provides the proper scaffolds, all students in the class will be able to succeed with grade-level texts and tasks.
Do you work with grades K-2 in ELA/Literacy?

question content: Mrs. Richards’ students have a range of reading proficiency and knowledge about the food chain. When reading a grade-level complex text about this topic, which group of students is most likely to perform better on comprehension questions?
choice: Cannot say. The research is inconclusive about the relationship between content knowledge and comprehension.

question content: How could Mrs. Richards best prepare students to build knowledge about the topic of the food chain?
choice: Have students read a series of additional texts at a variety of complexity levels on the topic.

question content: The main text that the students in Ms. Blackwell’s class is about to read is likely to be very difficult for the majority of the class. Which of the following is a strategy that Ms. Blackwell could use with her students with lower reading abilities?
choice: Provide students with lower reading abilities an audio version of the main text to listen to before reading the main text in class.

question content: Teachers should be color blind when it comes to their teaching - They shouldn’t think of their students in terms of their race or ethnicity.
Which of the following best describes your role?
I am color blind when it comes to my teaching - I don’t think of my students in terms of their race or ethnicity.
I try to keep in mind the limits of my students’ ability and give them assignments that I know they can do so that they do not become discouraged.
The gap in the achievement among students of different races is about poverty, not race.
Before students are asked to engage in complex learning tasks, they need to have a solid grasp of basic skills.
It is not fair to ask students who are struggling with English to take on challenging academic assignments.
Teachers should provide all students the opportunity to work with grade-level texts and tasks.
To be honest, students have a certain amount of intelligence, and they really can’t do much to change it.
Your intelligence is something about you that you can’t change very much.
If a child doesn’t learn something the first time, I will try another way.
If I provide the proper scaffolds, all students in my class will be able to succeed with grade-level texts and tasks.
Do you work with grades K-2 in ELA/Literacy?

I am confident that I am implementing the curriculum in a way that maximizes positive impact for student learning.
